1 STATE OF OKLAHOMA
2 2nd Session of the 60th Legislature (2026)
3 HOUSE BILL 3963 By: Munson
4
5
6
7 AS INTRODUCED
8 An Act relating to Oklahoma Higher Learning Access
Program; amending 70 O.S. 2021, Section 2603, as last
9 amended by Section 1, Chapter 485, O.S.L. 2025 (70
O.S. Supp. 2025, Section 2603), which relates to
10 eligibility requirements; changing term from
certified classroom teacher to school employee;
11 expanding eligibility to children of permanently
disabled veterans; amending 70 O.S. 2021, Section
12 2605, as last amended by Section 2, Chapter 485,
O.S.L. 2025 (70 O.S. Supp. 2025, Section 2605), which
13 relates to participation in the program; changing
term from certified classroom teacher to school
14 employee; expanding definition to include school
support employees; providing an effective date; and
15 declaring an emergency.
16
17
18 BE IT ENACTED BY THE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF OKLAHOMA:
19 SECTION 1. AMENDATORY 70 O.S. 2021, Section 2603, as
20 last amended by Section 1, Chapter 485, O.S.L. 2025 (70 O.S. Supp.
21 2025, Section 2603), is amended to read as follows:
22 Section 2603. A. Except as otherwise provided for in
23 subsection B of this section and elsewhere in this section, to be
24 eligible to participate in the Oklahoma Higher Learning Access
Req. No. 15248 Page 1

1 Prog ram and to qualify for an award which includes payment of an
2 amount equivalent to resident tuition or other tuition pursuant to
3 Section 2604 of this title for the first semester or other academic
4 unit of postsecondary enrollment, a student shall:
5 1. Be a resident of this state or be enrolled in a school
6 district located in this state that serves students who reside in
7 both this state and an adjacent state pursuant to a contract as
8 authorized in Section 5-117.1 of this title;
9 2. Be a United States citizen or lawfully present in the United
10 States. A student who is not a United States citizen or lawfully
11 present in the United States shall not be eligible to participate in
12 the Oklahoma Higher Learning Access Program and to qualify for an
13 award notwithstanding the provisions of Section 3242 of this title.
14 The provisions of this paragraph shall not apply to any student who
15 was enrolled in the Oklahoma Higher Learning Access Program prior to
16 the end of the 2006-2007 school year;
17 3. Have a record of satisfactory compliance with agreements
18 executed pursuant to Section 2605 of this title;
19 4. a. Have graduated within the previous three (3) years
20 from a high school accredited by the State Board of
21 Education or the Oklahoma School of Science and
22 Mathematics with a minimum 2.5 cumulative grade point
23 average on a 4.0 scale for all work attempted in
24 grades nine through twelve,
Req. No. 15248 Page 2

1 b. Have graduated within the previous three (3) years
2 from a high school not accredited by the State Board
3 of Education with a minimum 2.5 cumulative grade point
4 average on a 4.0 scale for all work attempted in
5 grades nine through twelve and have achieved a
6 composite score of 22 or higher on the ACT test, or
7 c. Have satisfactorily completed within the previous
8 three (3) years an educational program that was
9 provided through a means other than a public or
10 private school and have achieved a composite score of
11 22 or higher on the ACT test;
12 5. Have completed the curricular requirements for admission to
13 an institution within The Oklahoma State System of Higher Education.
14 Students shall also have attained a 2.5 grade point average in the
15 core curriculum courses. Students who attended a high school which
16 did not offer all the core curriculum courses or students who were
17 educated by other means and were not offered all the core curriculum
18 courses shall be allowed to satisfy this curriculum requirement by
19 participating in a program approved by the Oklahoma State Regents
20 for Higher Education for remediation of high school curricular
21 deficiencies;
22 6. Have satisfied admission standards as determined by the
23 Oklahoma State Regents for Higher Education for first-time-entering
24 students for the appropriate type of institution, or, if attending a
