18 C. To retain eligibility while pursuing the program of higher
19 learning in which enrolled, the student shall:
20 1. Meet the requirements for retention and degree completion as
21 established by the institution in which the student is enrolled;
22 2. Maintain good academic standing and satisfactory academic
23 progress according to standards of the Oklahoma State Regents for
24 Higher Education;
Req. No. 15248 Page 8

1 3. Maintain satisfactory academic progress as required for
2 eligibility for federal Title IV student financial aid programs.
3 The provisions of this paragraph shall become effective for the
4 2012-2013 school year;
5 4. Comply with the standards related to maintenance of
6 eligibility as promulgated by the Oklahoma State Regents for Higher
7 Education; and
8 5. Refrain from conduct that leads to expulsion or suspension
9 of more than one semester from an institution of higher education.
10 A student who violates the provisions of this paragraph shall
11 permanently lose eligibility for program benefits. The provisions
12 of this paragraph shall become effective January 1, 2008.
13 D. The Oklahoma State Regents for Higher Education and the
14 State Board of Career and Technology Education shall promulgate
15 rules relating to maintenance of eligibility under the Oklahoma
16 Higher Learning Access Act by a student.
17 E. It is the intent of the Legislature that students in the
18 ninth grade for the 1992-93 school year who are determined to be
19 eligible Oklahoma Higher Learning Access students pursuant to the
20 Oklahoma Higher Learning Access Act shall be the first students
21 eligible for benefits from the Oklahoma Higher Learning Access Trust
22 Fund.
23 F. The Oklahoma State Regents for Higher Education are
24 authorized to study, develop, and propose criteria for determining
Req. No. 15248 Page 9

1 awar d eligibility based upon the completion of seven semesters of
2 high school coursework by a student.
3 SECTION 2. AMENDATORY 70 O.S. 2021, Section 2605, as
4 last amended by Section 2, Chapter 485, O.S.L. 2025 (70 O.S. Supp.
5 2025, Section 2605), is amended to read as follows:
6 Section 2605. A. Each school year, every fifth- through
7 eleventh-grade student in the public and private schools of this
8 state and students who are educated by other means and are in the
9 equivalent of the fifth through eleventh grade shall be apprised,
10 together with the parent, custodial parent, or guardian of the
11 student, of the opportunity for access to higher learning under the
12 Oklahoma Higher Learning Access Program. The Oklahoma State Regents
13 for Higher Education and the State Board of Education shall develop,
14 promote, and coordinate a public awareness program to be utilized in
15 making students and parents aware of the Oklahoma Higher Learning
16 Access Program.
17 B. On a form provided by the Oklahoma State Regents for Higher
18 Education, every public school district shall designate at least one
19 Oklahoma Higher Learning Access Program contact person, who shall be
20 a counselor or teacher, at each public school site in this state in
21 which eighth-, ninth-, tenth-, or eleventh-grade classes are taught.
22 When requested by the State Regents, the State Board of Education
23 shall assist the State Regents to ensure the designation of contact
24 persons. Private schools shall also designate at least one school
Req. No. 15248 Page 10

1 offi cial as a contact person. For students who are educated by
2 other means, a parent or guardian or other person approved by the
3 State Regents shall be designated the contact person.
4 C. 1. Students who qualify on the basis of financial need
5 according to subsection D or E of this section or who meet the
6 eligibility qualification set forth in subparagraph a of paragraph 1
7 of subsection B of Section 2603 of this title no later than December
8 31 of their twelfth-grade year or prior to reaching the age of
9 seventeen (17) and who qualify on the basis of the standards and
10 provisions promulgated by the Oklahoma State Regents for Higher
11 Education shall be given the opportunity throughout the eighth-,
12 ninth-, tenth-, and eleventh-grade years and no later than December
13 31 of the twelfth-grade year, for students enrolled in a public or
14 private school, or between the ages of thirteen (13) and seventeen
15 (17), for students who are educated by other means, to enter into
16 participation in the program by agreeing to, throughout the
17 remainder of their school years or educational program:
18 a. attend school or an educational program regularly and
19 do homework regularly,
20 b. refrain from substance abuse,
21 c. refrain from commission of crimes or delinquent acts,
22 d. have school work and school records reviewed by
23 mentors designated pursuant to the program,
24
Req. No. 15248 Page 11

1 e. provide information requested by the Oklahoma State
2 Regents for Higher Education or the State Board of
3 Education, and
4 f. participate in program activities.
5 2. Students who meet the eligibility qualification set forth in
6 subparagraph a of paragraph 1 of subsection B of Section 2603 of
7 this title after December 31 of their twelfth-grade year or after
8 reaching the age of eighteen (18) shall be given the opportunity
9 prior to reaching the age of twenty-one (21) to enter into
10 participation in the program and shall execute an agreement with
11 provisions as determined by the Oklahoma State Regents for Higher
12 Education.
13 3. The contact person shall maintain the agreements, which
14 shall be executed on forms provided by the Oklahoma State Regents
15 for Higher Education and managed according to regulations
16 promulgated by the Oklahoma State Regents for Higher Education, and
17 the contact person shall monitor compliance of the student with the
18 terms of the agreement. The Oklahoma State Regents for Higher
19 Education are authorized to process student agreements and verify
20 compliance with the agreements. Students failing to comply with the
21 terms of the agreement shall not be eligible for the awards provided
22 in Section 2604 of this title.
23
24
